From 60afe8bb557e4a3d57995a3b4b9c9bb49c0e013e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Alfred Chen <cchalpha@gmail.com>
Date: Wed, 26 Apr 2023 16:18:58 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 372/400] sched/alt: PDS Priority Squeeze

Priority Squeeze

Currently, Project C scheduler(BMQ and PDS) are using 198 level of
priority to mapping linux rt(100 in number) and normal(40 in number)
policy. 198 levels are a bit over-killed for priorities, searching
or maintaining such huge schedule queue is an overhead for the
scheduler.

Priority squeeze will let Project C scheduler maintain only 64
levels of priority, mapping linux rt policy into 25 priority
(100->25) of the first 32 levels(7 levels will be reserved), then
mapping normal policy into the last 32 levels(40 nice level into 20
priority and 12 priorities before current time from the deadline
perspective).

0.1 First working patch
0.2 PDS update_rq_time_edge() optimization
0.3 Update code for 32bits system and enable ALT_SCHED_DEBUG
0.4 Reverted update_sched_preempt_mask handling for decativated task in
    __schedule()
0.5 Fix rq->prio update issue in update_rq_time_edge(), use rq->prio
    instead of caculating it from the bitmap in runtime
0.6 Code clean-up
0.7 Replace SCHED_BITS with SCHED_LEVELS
